<HEAD>
<TITLE>Wireless Communication: From Smoke Signals to the Unwired Internet
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<h1>Wireless Communication: From Smoke Signals to the Unwired
Internet (4)</h1>
<font size="4">
<ul>
  <li>political and social impacts</li>
       <ul>
         <li>military applications and govt. funding</li>
         <li>development of radio; propaganda uses in various
              wars etc</li>
         <li>military uses</li>
       </ul>
  <li>Milestones</li>
       <ul>
         <li>earliest networks; fire, optical telegraph, etc.; notion of
              digital signaling</li>
         <li>signal &quot;alphabet&quot; (vs. fixed set of
              messages); enabled encryption, etc</li>
         <li>electrical telegraph (digital signaling)
              </li>
         <li>telephone (analog)</li>
         <li>Marconi and radio: &quot;&#133;what can one expect
              of a few wretched wires under similar conditions?&quot; - Guyot;
              Holzmann p.93</li>
         <li>ARPAnet to TCP/IP; Ethernet and cheap fast networks
              </li>
         <li>the 4 important stages in development of telegraphy
              </li>
         <li>&quot;critical mass&quot; for TCP/IP and the
              WWW</li>
       </ul>
  <li>communication technical problems</li>
       <ul>
         <li>symbol coding</li>
         <li>control flow, error correction, out-of-band signaling
              </li>
         <li>encryption (Hooke: as separate field)
              </li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>State of the art</li>
       <ul>
         <li>Cellular and packet-radio networks</li>
         <li>Frequency allocations; international standards
              </li>
         <li>Security</li>
         <li>TCP/IP uber alles</li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>Show &amp; tell</li>
       <ul>
         <li>Telegraph relay</li>
         <li>WWII-era radios</li>
         <li>Early cordless phones &amp; cell phones
              </li>
         <li>Super-compact (small DECT, Moto MicroTac) cell
              phones</li>
         <li>2-way messaging devices (e.g. Moto MemOS client)
              </li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>Interesting projects</li>
       <ul>
         <li>compare bandwidth &amp; latency of French telegraph &amp;
              wireless Internet; were early telegraph systems pipelined?</li>
         <li>create a routing table for (fictitious?) telegraph
              network</li>
         <li>compare out-of-band signals of Chappe or Edelcranz
              telegraph with TCP (&quot;attention&quot;, &quot;error&quot;,
              &quot;transmission is too fast&quot;), etc</li>
         <li>devise coding system, or compare 2 signaling
              systems by doing an actual experiment</li>
         <li>programming? maybe HyperCard-like or simple tcl/tk
              or&#133;?</li>
       </ul>
</ul>
</ul>
<h1>From the Abacus to the Handheld PC (4)</h1>
<ul>
  <li>earliest computers</li>
  <li>Babbage and Lovelace: general-purpose programmable computers
       </li>
  <li>Milestones</li>
       <ul>
         <li>stored-program concept; programs as data</li>
         <li>Turing</li>
         <li>invention of transistor (1940, Bell Labs)
              </li>
         <li>invention of integrated circuit (1969?; Intel
              founded 1970)</li>
         <li>microprocessor (1971, Intel 4004) and the Attack
              of the Killer Micros; PC's become <I>consumer </I>device
              </li>
         <li>VisiCalc</li>
         <li>vision of consumer software: &quot;a computer
              on every desktop [running Microsoft software]&quot;</li>
         <li>graphical interfaces and mice; Engelbart, Xerox
              PARC, Apple, and Microsoft</li>
         <li>Portable computers; the Osborne 1</li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>Show &amp; tell</li>
       <ul>
         <li>abacus (digital) v slide rule (analog)</li>
         <li>Early digital calculators</li>
         <li>Osborne 1, an early portable computer
              </li>
         <li>InfoPad</li>
         <li>PIMs/PDAs (various)</li>
         <li>Nokia 9000</li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>Interesting projects</li>
</ul>
<h1>The Democratization of the PC (4)</h1>
<ul>
  <li>From the sword of the Emperor to the tool of the people</li>
       <ul>
         <li>democratization of PC's: the microprocessor</li>
         <li>&quot;none will survive the attack of the killer
              micros!&quot;</li>
       </ul>
  <li> Luddites, 1811, destroying machinery that was replacing human
       employees 
  <li>constant cost (or weight) through the ages ($2000, 50 lbs)
       </li>
  <li>how communication has already changed things</li>
       <ul>
         <li>military: &quot;when the loop is too tight&quot;</li>
         <li>Tiananmen Sq</li>
         <li>Canada trial</li>
         <li>jurisdictional issues (pornography, etc)
              </li>
         <li>encryption, the CDA, censorship on the net, &quot;24
              hours&quot; campaign, munitions export, anonymous ecash
              </li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>future changes: everyone is a printing press</li>
  <li>Charge for sale  charge for service</li>
       <ul>
         <li>software ->  support</li>
         <li>cel phone ->  cel service</li>
         <li>ns navigator  -> ns intranet app foundry</li>
         <li>pc hardware ->  nc's and nc servers</li>
         <li>web ->  webTV
       </ul>
  <li>'tragedy of the commons': pricing the Internet</li>
  <li> Late 1996: Internet moving from "pull" to "push" service model
       (netcasting, PointCast, Marimba, etc.): good or bad?
</ul>
<h1>The Convergence of Computing and Communication (2)</h1>
<ul>
  <li>the Net: not just for email anymore (qualitative vs. quantitative
       change: the WWW)</li>
       <ul>
         <li>data sharing</li>
         <li>distributed computing</li>
         <li>&quot;access is the killer app&quot;</li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>from building-sized to atom-sized: the Big Shrink (qualitative
       vs. quantitative change: laptops, palmtops, pocket-sized)</li>
       <ul>
         <li>&quot;everyone has a cel phone&quot; + &quot;everyone can
              carry a computer in their pocket&quot;  =  &quot;everyone has
              an internet appliance&quot;  qualitative vs. quantitative change
              </li>
         <li>cellular phones, pagers, cordless phones, 2-way
              radios</li>
         <li>less powerful CPU's/embedded controllers for
              tiny appliances</li>
         <li>it's a phone!  it's a computer!  it's a phone
              <I>and</I> a computer! it's&#133;</li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>Newly-enabled technologies</li>
       <ul>
         <li>&quot;anywhere, anytime&quot; access</li>
         <li>autonomous agents</li>
         <li>active badges, ubiquitous computing: &quot;the
              network <I>is</I> the computer&quot; (who said this?)</li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>What's it take, <I>really</I>?</li>
       <ul>
         <li>Megabits to punybaud: (who said this?) a painful transition
              from wired to wireless paradigm</li>
         <li>Cost &amp; quality of connectivity, tiny devices,
              &quot;different&quot; UI and usage model</li>
         <li>&quot;Meaningful&quot;, relevant content presentation
              </li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>The Future</li>
       <ul>
         <li>of mobile computing devices/personal communicators</li>
         <li>of the Internet, esp. unwired</li>
         <li>of network-centric vs. &quot;conventional&quot;
              computing</li>
              
       </ul>
  <li>Guest Speakers</li>
       <ul>
         <li>Trevor, Chris Long: InfoPad, portability, user interfaces,
              problems of portable devices</li>
         <li>Marvin Theimer or someone from PARC: ubiquitous
              computing</li>
         <li>Donald Norman: on usability, consumer nature
              of PIMs etc.</li>
       </ul>
  <li>Course logistics</li>
       <ul>
         <li>Klaus: need real projects w/tech content, not fluff</li>
         <li>Susan: some &quot;hook&quot; to get people not
              to ditch after break</li>
         <li>Armando: how about a bibliography for the course?
              </li>
       </ul>
  <li>Course readings - ideas</li>
       <ul>
         <li>Soul of a New Machine</li>
         <li>Where Wizards Stay Up Late</li>
       </ul>
</ul>

<h1>Cross-cutting issues</h1>
<ul>
  <li>Who &quot;invents&quot; something?  Examples: automobile;
       computer; IC; Netscape?; </li> 
  <li>Isomorphisms made it possible</li>
       <ul>
         <li>binary math and boolean logic</li>
         <li>encodings of arbitrary info into binary, therefore
              into symbols</li>
         <li>symbol manipulation: sorting a list of numbers
              - a list of words</li>
       </ul>
  <li>enabling technologies: &quot;cranes&quot; vs. &quot;skyhooks&quot;
  <li>&quot;the knee of the exponential&quot;; critical mass. minis/micros,
       then PC's, then the Web; next, wireless/mobile?</li>
</ul>
</font>

